	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Rules of Origin: Pacific ACP wants global sourcing on fresh and frozen tuna</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>During the last meeting of Pacific ACP trade ministers, the Solomon Islands minister of foreign affairs and external trade told his colleagues to negotiate hard for global sourcing for fresh and frozen fish in a comprehensive EPA with the EU.</p><p>He stated that: ‘We need to negotiate very hard to ensure that, like our processed fish [canned tuna], we can also get global sourcing for fresh and frozen fish ... This would ensure that every single one of us, particularly the least developed countries (LDCs) and the small island states (SISs) will also stand to benefit from a comprehensive EPA.’</p><p>In the interim EPA already signed with the EU by Papua New Guinea and Fiji, the global sourcing rule for processed fish has already been secured. But global sourcing does not apply to fresh and frozen fish, which some LDCs and SISs are more interested in because they lack the capacity and the resources (water, land, infrastructure) to build a cannery.</p><p>‘Fish is one resource, perhaps the only resource, our region has been blessed with and which we can all claim to have in relative abundance … The EPA can only be a meaningful agreement for all of us if this global sourcing rule is also extended to fresh and frozen fish’, the minister stressed.</p><p>A number of countries, including Fiji, Kiribati and Tuvalu, spoke strongly at the meeting on the need to continue to negotiate global sourcing for fresh and frozen fish, and this was agreed to by the meeting. The trade ministers also agreed to an ambitious road map, drawn up by the forum secretariat, to conclude the negotiations by the end of the year.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Press article, <i>Solomon Star</i>, 7 February 2011<br/>
<a href="http://www.solomonstarnews.com/news/national/10053-shanel-pacific-acps-to-negotiate-hard-on-fresh-and-frozen-fish" target="_self">http://www.solomonstarnews.com/news/national/10053-shanel-pacific-acps-t...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Extending the global sourcing derogation to the rules of origin to include products other than canned tuna would indeed be of crucial importance for Pacific ACP countries. However, to achieve this, the Pacific ACP will have to convince their European partners that this will contribute to sustainable fisheries development, including from an environmental and social point of view. Concerns were raised by the European Parliament on 19 January 2011 regarding such issues, and such concerns should be responded to by the Pacific ACP in their future dialogue for the conclusion of the EPA, in order to pave the way to a potential extension of the global-sourcing derogation.</p>
		</div>
		
